CodeList.Name: Respiratory Test Name

Description.TranslatedText: A terminology codelist based on the test names for physiological findings related to the respiratory system, including the organs that are involved in breathing such as the nose, throat, larynx, trachea, bronchi and lungs.

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: A measurement of respiratory tract resistance to airflow during inspiration and expiration.

EnumeratedItem.CodedValue: Diffusion Capacity of Lung for CO
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Diffusion Capacity of Lung for CO
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The volume of the carbon monoxide that is transferred from inspired air into the pulmonary capillary blood.
The diffusing capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide expressed as a proportion of the alveolar volume.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide/Alveolar Volume Ratio

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The maximum volume of air a subject can exhale from the lungs after a tidal exhalation.
The change in FEV1 following administration of a bronchodilator relative to the pre-treatment FEV1 value.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 Second Reversibility

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The proportion of total forced vital capacity that is expelled during the first second of a forced exhalation.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 Second to Forced Vital Capacity Ratio Measurement

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The ratio of the forced expiratory volume during the first second of exhalation to the largest observed expired volume during the first six seconds of a forced vital capacity maneuver.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 Second to Forced Vital Capacity in 6 Seconds

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The mean forced expiratory flow rate at 25-75% of the forced vital capacity. (NCI)
The volume of air that a subject can breathe out during the first second of exhalation after maximum inhalation.
The volume of air that a subject can breathe out during the first 6 seconds of exhalation after maximum inhalation.
The volume of air that a subject can breathe in during the first second of inhalation after maximum exhalation.
The maximum volume of air that can be exhaled after forced maximum inhalation.
The volume of air remaining in the lungs after a normal exhalation. (NCI)
The diffusing capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide adjusted for hemoglobin concentration.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Hemoglobin Corrected Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The diffusing capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide expressed as a proportion of the alveolar volume, adjusted for hemoglobin concentration.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Hemoglobin Corrected Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide/Alveolar Volume Ratio

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The change in IC following administration of a bronchodilator relative to the pre-treatment IC value.
The maximum volume of air a subject can inhale into the lungs after a tidal exhalation (IRV plus TV).
The maximum volume of air a subject can inhale into the lungs after a tidal inhalation.
Forced inspiratory flow for a portion of the FVC curve at the point where the maximum portion of FVC is already inhaled.

EnumeratedItem.CodedValue: Mean Diffusion Capacity of Lung for CO
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCSynonym: Mean Diffusion Capacity of Lung for CO
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The mean volume of the carbon monoxide that is transferred from inspired air into the pulmonary capillary blood.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Mean Carbon Monoxide Diffusing Capability Test

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The rate at which oxygen is absorbed and utilized by any given tissue in the body.
The volume of oxygen per heartbeat consumed by the body while at rest.
The maximal flow achieved during the maximally forced expiration initiated at maximum inhalation.
The maximal flow achieved during the maximally forced inspiration through the nose initiated at maximum exhalation. (NCI)
The change in PEF following administration of a bronchodilator relative to the pre-treatment PEF value.
The diffusing capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Percent Predicted Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The proportion of the diffusing capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide to alveolar volume, expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Percent Predicted Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide/Alveolar Volume Ratio

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The maximum volume of air a subject can exhale from the lungs after a tidal exhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
The mean forced expiratory flow rate at 25-75% of the forced vital capacity as a proportion of the predicted normal value. (NCI)
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Percent Predicted Forced Expiratory Flow at 25-75 Percent

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: Forced expiratory volume in one second as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Percent Predicted Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 Second

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The proportion of total forced vital capacity that is expelled during the first second of a forced exhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Percent Predicted Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 Second Divided by Forced Vital Capacity

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: Forced expiratory volume in six seconds as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Percent Predicted Forced Expiratory Volume in 6 Seconds

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: Forced inspiratory flow for a portion of the FVC curve at the point where the maximum portion of FVC is already inhaled as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Percent Predicted Forced Inspiratory Flow Maximum

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The volume of air that a subject can breathe in during the first second of inhalation after maximum exhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Percent Predicted Forced Inspiratory Volume in 1 Second

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: Forced vital capacity as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
The diffusing capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value, adjusted for hemoglobin concentration.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Percent Predicted Hemoglobin Corrected Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The proportion of diffusing capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide to the alveolar volume expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value, adjusted for hemoglobin concentration.
EnumeratedItem.nciodm:PreferredTerm: Percent Predicted Hemoglobin Corrected Diffusion Capacity of the Lung for Carbon Monoxide/Alveolar Volume Ratio

EnumeratedItem.nciodm:CDISCDefinition: The maximum volume of air a subject can inhale into the lungs after a tidal exhalation (IRV plus TV) as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
The maximum volume of air a subject can inhale into the lungs after a tidal inhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
The maximal flow achieved during the maximally forced expiration initiated at maximum inhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
The volume of air remaining in the lungs after maximum exhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
The maximum volume of air that can be exhaled after slow maximum inhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
The volume of air moved into and out of the lungs during breathing at rest as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
The total volume of air in the lungs after maximum inhalation as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
A measurement of the ability of the lung to store energy, which is required for passive expiration.
The volume of air remaining in the lungs after maximum exhalation.
The ratio between the amount of carbon dioxide produced and oxygen consumed in one breath.
The maximum volume of air that can be exhaled after slow maximum inhalation.
A measurement of the airway conductance relative to lung volume. (NCI)
A measurement used to describe airway behavior irrespective of lung volume; it is calculated as airway resistance (Raw) multiplied by functional residual capacity (FRC).
The volume of air moved into and out of the lungs during breathing at rest.
The total volume of air in the lungs after maximum inhalation.
A calculated value based on all factors that influence the flow of gas from the airway opening to the alveoli, including airway resistance, and tissue resistance of the lung and chest wall. (NCI)
